{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778729711,"nonce":"XT59D6EZxnBL3O/e0Yjekb5pMg0=","message":"A follow-up tension worth flagging before the implementation plan lands. The Codex synthesis predicts an RNN trained under matched-ε H∞ may dissociate feedback-gain from nominal speed (the \"decoupling\" outcome). But cs2019's humans show *coupled* gain+speed inflation — the very signature the analytical Riccati predicts. The Riccati is a linear regulator (`u_t = -K_t·x_t` for time-varying `K_t`), and a linear regulator **structurally cannot** decouple feedforward from feedback because they share the same `K_t`. So:\n\n1. Humans fit cs2019's linear Riccati behaviourally → 2. that controller can't decouple by parameterisation → 3. humans appear to not decouple → 4. but a GRU *can* decouple architecturally → 5. if a matched-ε-trained GRU dissociates gain from speed, **the GRU is doing something humans don't appear to be doing** — even though humans presumably have at least as much representational capacity.\n\nThis is the actually-interesting outcome to look for in the upcoming experiment. Three ways it could resolve:\n\n**(a) GRU dissociates, humans don't.** The cs2019 +Δv signature is a property of the *linear-regulator parameterisation* humans happen to use (for whatever reason — evolutionary, developmental, neural-architecture-imposed, or a cost-function bias toward coupling). The GRU under matched ε is *more* optimal than humans in the sense of achieving the same robustness at a lower nominal-speed cost. This would be a substantive scientific finding: **humans are leaving optimal control on the table because their effective parameterisation is regulator-like.**\n\n**(b) GRU also shows +Δv (no dissociation).** Codex's decoupling hypothesis is wrong. The +Δv signature is a property of the *training game* (full-state ε H∞), not of the parameterisation. Humans showing +Δv is just consistent with them being trained under unpredictable disturbances; nothing special about being linear.\n\n**(c) GRU partially dissociates** — modest +Δv reduction with some gain modulation. The \"decoupled tracker vs coupled regulator\" dichotomy is too crisp; real RNNs (and probably real humans) sit somewhere in between, and the cs2019 signature is a quantitative property of \"how much you couple,\" not a binary.\n\n\ncs2019's model fit is at the *behavioural* level (peak velocity, FB gain, lateral deviation profiles) — not at the level of the underlying neural implementation. Humans could be neurally complex but behaviourally constrained:\n- Biomechanical / inertial bottlenecks that force coupling\n- A cost function that rewards coupled solutions (e.g., neural cost of maintaining high FF without proportional FB)\n- Always-on architectural coupling between motor-cortex modes that the brain doesn't get to choose\n- Developmental constraints fixing the controller in a regulator-like regime\n\nSo \"behaving linearly\" doesn't necessarily mean \"implemented as a linear function\" — it could mean \"outputting in a regime consistent with a linear-regulator parameterisation for these task constraints.\" The GRU experiment can tell us whether decoupling is *available* under the matched-ε game; it cannot directly tell us why humans don't use it.\n\n\nThe decision tree under Phase 2 (GRU arm) should explicitly enumerate these three outcomes and the scientific framing each implies. Outcome (a) is the most interesting if it occurs — it's not just \"the GRU dissociated\"; it's \"we've found a way that humans are sub-optimal that the parameterisation argument predicts.\" The follow-up to that finding would be: under what conditions does an RNN converge to a coupled-regulator-like solution (matching the human signature) vs a decoupled-tracker-like one? Architectural constraints? Cost-function structure? Training-noise regime? `0c95d6b` (GRU affine decomposition + bimodality clustering) plus possibly architectural-restriction sweeps become the natural follow-up — but only after we know whether the GRU actually dissociates at all.","files":null}]}